 nickname for a happy or fortunate man, from Middle English <i>seli</i> ‘happy, fortunate’ (Old English <i>sǣlig</i>) + <i>man</i>. The nickname was also used as a personal name. See also   Seeley  .","English: from the Middle English nickname or female personal name <i>Sely</i> (see   Seeley  ) + <i>-man</i>, hence an occupational name for a servant of someone so called.","Americanized form of German <b>Sellmann</b> (see   Sellman  )."]},{"name":"Seelye","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Sealy","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  .","Welsh: from the male personal name <i>Selyf</i> or <i>Seleu</i>, medieval Welsh vernacular forms of   Solomon   which were replaced by that form in the Welsh Bible of 1588.","Irish: variant of   Shelley   (in counties Cork and Kerry); elsewhere of English or Welsh origin, as in 1 above and 2."]},{"name":"Sealey","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Seley","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Seeley was born in 1393, in Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Seeley. He had at least 2 sons with Martha Benjamin. He died in 1442, in England, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1393–1442":"1393–1442","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1418–Male":"1418–Surnud","1420–1447":"1420–1447","1373–1400":"1373–1400","1447":"1447","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1418":"1418","after 1400":"pärast 1400","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, England":"Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1393–1442":"1393–1442","1395–1420":"1395–1420